# NutriGarden üå±

NutriGarden is a **frontend-only prototype web app** that helps users build healthy nutrition habits by turning daily nutrition tracking into a growing **flower garden**.

Each tracked nutrient becomes a flower:

* Meet your daily goals ‚Üí flowers grow
* Miss your goals ‚Üí flowers regress 

The app runs entirely in the browser and requires **no backend** and **no API keys**.


## Tech Stack

* **HTML** ‚Äì screen-based UI
* **CSS** ‚Äì fixed mobile-style layout & pixel-art garden
* **Vanilla JavaScript** ‚Äì all logic, state & rendering
* **OpenFoodFacts API** ‚Äì nutrition lookup (public, no auth)

No frameworks, build tools, or dependencies required.

---

## Project Structure

```text
/
‚îú‚îÄ index.html        # Main HTML entry
‚îú‚îÄ app.js            # Application logic & state
‚îú‚îÄ styles.css        # Styling
‚îú‚îÄ images/
‚îÇ  ‚îú‚îÄ bloem1/        # Hydration flower stages (1‚Äì14)
‚îÇ  ‚îú‚îÄ bloem2/        # Protein flower stages
‚îÇ  ‚îú‚îÄ bloem3/        # Carbs flower stages
‚îÇ  ‚îî‚îÄ bloem4/        # Fat flower stages
‚îî‚îÄ README.md
```

> ‚ö†Ô∏è Each `bloemX` folder must contain images named `1.png` ‚Üí `14.png`.

## How It Works (High Level)

1. User enters personal details
2. Chooses **realistic goals** or **custom goals**
3. Selects which nutrients to track:
   * Hydration
   * Protein
   * Carbs
   * Fat
4. Logs food by name + grams
5. Nutrition values are fetched from OpenFoodFacts
6. Each nutrient progresses through flower growth stages
7. Completing stage 14 plants a new flower seed

## Running the App

### VS Code Live Server

This is the easiest and most reliable option.

1. Install the **Live Server** extension in VS Code
2. Open the project folder
3. Right-click `index.html`
4. Select **‚ÄúOpen with Live Server‚Äù**

The app will open in your browser (usually at `http://127.0.0.1:5500`).

### Option 2: Any Local Web Server

You **must** use a local server because:

* `fetch()` (OpenFoodFacts) will fail with `file://`
* Some browsers block local JS features otherwise

#### Using Python

```bash
python -m http.server 8000
```

Then open:

```
http://localhost:8000
```

#### Using Node.js

```bash
npx serve
```


